{"number":58426,"title":"[mgmt-generator] PATCH model with array of known mgmt type (e.g. WritableSubResource) at root emits invalid `Type.DeserializeType(...)` call","body":"## Summary

When a top-level resource update (PATCH body) model contains an array property of a known management type (e.g. `Azure.ResourceManager.Models.WritableSubResource`) **directly at the root** (no inner `properties` wrapper), the generated `Deserialize{Model}` method emits an invalid call to `WritableSubResource.DeserializeWritableSubResource(item, options)` — a method that is `internal` to `Azure.ResourceManager` and therefore not accessible from the generated assembly. This produces `CS0117: &#39;WritableSubResource&#39; does not contain a definition for &#39;DeserializeWritableSubResource&#39;`.

The same property type works correctly when:
- it lives on a regular (non-update) model, or
- it is nested inside an inner `*Properties` model (even if that `*Properties` is itself the body of a PATCH).

## Repro (minimum TypeSpec)

```tsp
import \&#34;@typespec/rest\&#34;;
import \&#34;@typespec/http\&#34;;
import \&#34;@azure-tools/typespec-azure-core\&#34;;
import \&#34;@azure-tools/typespec-azure-resource-manager\&#34;;

using TypeSpec.Http;
using TypeSpec.Rest;
using Azure.ResourceManager;

@armProviderNamespace
@service(#{ title: \&#34;Repro\&#34; })
@versioned(Versions)
namespace Microsoft.Repro;

enum Versions { @useDependency(Azure.ResourceManager.Versions.v1_0_Preview_1) v2024_01_01: \&#34;2024-01-01\&#34; }

model FooResource is TrackedResource {
  @key(\&#34;fooName\&#34;) @segment(\&#34;foos\&#34;) @path
  name: string;
}

model FooProperties {
  description?: string;
}

// The trigger: array of WritableSubResource at the ROOT of the PATCH body
// (not nested inside an inner *Properties wrapper).
model FooPatch {
  endpoints?: Azure.ResourceManager.Models.WritableSubResource[];
  tags?: Record;
}

@armResourceOperations
interface Foos {
  get is ArmResourceRead;
  createOrUpdate is ArmResourceCreateOrReplaceAsync;
  update is ArmCustomPatchAsync;
  delete is ArmResourceDeleteWithoutOkAsync;
}
```

### Expected

`FooPatch.Serialization.cs` deserializes each `endpoints` item via the same path used elsewhere for known mgmt types:

```csharp
array.Add(ModelReaderWriter.Read(
    new BinaryData(Encoding.UTF8.GetBytes(item.GetRawText())),
    ModelSerializationExtensions.WireOptions,
    Generated.Context.Default));
```

### Actual

```csharp
List array = new List();
foreach (var item in prop.Value.EnumerateArray())
{
    array.Add(WritableSubResource.DeserializeWritableSubResource(item, options)); // CS0117
}
```

(Note also: the per-item null check `if (item.ValueKind == JsonValueKind.Null) array.Add(null)` is missing — symptom of the same root cause.)

## Root cause analysis

In upstream `MrwSerializationTypeDefinition.CreateDeserializeValueExpression` (typespec/packages/http-client-csharp), only the `IsFrameworkType: true` branch delegates to `TypeFactory.DeserializeJsonValue`:

```csharp
var result = valueType switch
{
    { IsFrameworkType: true } when valueType.FrameworkType == typeof(Nullable&lt;&gt;) =&gt;
        ScmCodeModelGenerator.Instance.TypeFactory.DeserializeJsonValue(...),
    { IsFrameworkType: true } =&gt;
        ScmCodeModelGenerator.Instance.TypeFactory.DeserializeJsonValue(...),
    { IsEnum: true } =&gt; ...,
    _ =&gt; GetDeserializationMethodInvocationForType(valueType, jsonElement, data, _mrwOptionsParameterSnippet) // ← falls here
};
```

The fallback `GetDeserializationMethodInvocationForType` emits `Static(type).Invoke(\$\&#34;Deserialize{type.Name}\&#34;, ...)` directly and **never consults `TypeFactory`**. Therefore `ManagementTypeFactory.DeserializeJsonValue`&#39;s name-based recovery (`KnownManagementTypes.IsKnownManagementType`) cannot rescue the call.

For the affected property only, the array&#39;s element `CSharpType` arrives at this method with `IsFrameworkType == false`, even though `KnownManagementTypes` maps the corresponding CLID (`Azure.ResourceManager.Models.WritableSubResource`) to `typeof(WritableSubResource)`. The other 3 sites in dnsresolver that use the same `InputModelType` (id 368, same CLID) get the framework type correctly. Symmetric evidence on the serialize side — the per-item null-check is also omitted only in the broken case (`TypeRequiresNullCheckInSerialization` requires `IsFrameworkType == true` for non-value reference types).

The exact transformation that strips the framework flag for this one property is not yet pinned down (ruled out: `FlattenPropertyVisitor`, `InheritableSystemObjectModelVisitor`, `NameVisitor`, TCGC `@@alternateType` not being applied — there&#39;s only one InputModelType for `WritableSubResource` with the canonical CLID).

## Suggested fix directions

1. **Quick, mgmt-side**: add a visitor in the mgmt generator that walks update-model property types (and their element types) and forces framework `CSharpType` for any CLID in `KnownManagementTypes._idToSystemTypeMap`, so `IsFrameworkType` is true by the time serialization is built.
2. **Upstream**: have `GetDeserializationMethodInvocationForType` consult `TypeFactory.DeserializeJsonValue` (or have `CreateDeserializeValueExpression` route the `_` branch through `TypeFactory`), so the name-based recovery in mgmt&#39;s override is reachable.

## Affected package

`sdk/dnsresolver/Azure.ResourceManager.DnsResolver` — currently worked around in `src/Custom/DnsForwardingRulesetPatch.cs` via a `[CodeGenSerialization(...DeserializationValueHook=...)]` hook.

## Repro command

